#ICYMI - The Board voted, 5-0, at the Sept. 1 Commission Meeting to improve Univeter Road at two intersections in the Holly Springs area. Commissioners awarded a $1.27 million construction contract with low-bidder Bartow Paving Company.

The improvements include the realignment of New Light Road at its approach with Univeter Road, installation of a left-turn lane on Univeter Road and the installation of a traffic signal at the intersection. Additionally, Pinecrest Road‚Äôs approach to Univeter Road will be realigned to improve sight distance. There also will be a left-turn lane installed on Univeter Road. #CherokeeCounts #CherokeeGA #CherokeeCounty

Originally created as a way to commemorate Mother Teresa‚Äôs death, International Day of Charity on took off worldwide in 2012 when it was declared an international holiday. The holiday provides a platform for charitable opportunities to take place.

If you need help finding a local charity, check out the Never Alone Food Pantry, SERV International and MUST Ministries. If you can‚Äôt make a financial donation today, there are still many ways to get involved.

Overall, this day reminds us that simple acts of charity can alleviate the worst effects of crises and create more resilient communities. #CherokeeGA #CherokeeCounty

post_text: Here's some #ThrowbackThursday history on the Oak Grove and Bascomb communities, courtesy of the Cherokee County Historical Society! #CherokeeCounty #CherokeeGA #tbt
shared_text:
Cherokee County Historical Society
July 21 at 9:04 AM ¬∑

This week we‚Äôre heading out to Bascomb and Oak Grove for our #TravelingTuesdays adventure!

‚ÄúBascomb and Oak Grove are two communities that grew up in Southwest Cherokee County around churches and schools. The two communities were close together and in many ways similar so that their separate identities are often hard to distinguish. Bascomb community was on the Bell‚Äôs Ferry Road near the Bascomb Road intersection. Bascomb Methodist Church was a one-room facility until the 1930s. During the summer baseball games were played on the church grounds. Farmers in the area raised crops of cotton and corn. Farmers would transport their crops to Marietta by horse-drawn wagon. The Oak Grove community was further south and had a gristmill and sawmill owned by W.O. Tyson.‚Äù

Information for this post from Cherokee County, Georgia: A History
Written by Rebecca Johnston
#CherokeeCountyHistoricalSociety #CCHS #localhistory #Bascomb #OakGrove

With September here, it's a great time to kickstart healthy eating habits into high gear. September is "Fruit and Veggies - More Matters Month," and the goal is to bring awareness of how beneficial fruits and vegetables are in our everyday diets.

Studies show that more than 90% of both adults and children do not eat the recommended amount of daily fruits and vegetables. However, remembering to fill half of your plate with fruits and vegetables at every eating occasion, including snacks, will count toward your daily intake and improve your overall health.

During this month, we will provide weekly tips and information to local resources to work towards a healthier diet.

This week‚Äôs tip is vegetable blanching. http://ow.ly/ue7B50Bb3ew. Not only does blanching help preserve your vegetables, it‚Äôs cost-saving and great for long term food storage for emergency preparedness. #MoreMattersMonth #CherokeeGA #CherokeeCounty

post_text: Here's some #ThrowbackThursday history on the Free Home community, courtesy of the Cherokee County Historical Society! #CherokeeCounty #CherokeeGA #tbt
shared_text:
Cherokee County Historical Society
July 14 at 9:06 AM ¬∑

Today we are on our way to Free Home for this #TravelingTuesdays!

‚ÄúAnother community in the area was Free Home at the intersection of Highways 20 and 372, which was known as the Birmingham Highway. The oldest school in the community was established in the 1870s. Captain Delavan Lively, a captain during the War Between the States, owned land near the school in the Cross Roads Militia District. Farming the land at the time was proving hard, and to attract new residents to the area, Lively offered to give free land to anyone who would build a house. The name Free Home derived from that offer.‚Äù

Information for this post from Cherokee County, Georgia: A History
Written by Rebecca Johnston
#CherokeeCountyHistoricalSociety #CCHS #localhistory #FreeHome

Heads up Cherokee! Census takers have started door-to-door canvassing in the low response areas of our county. If you have a census taker show up at your door, remember to ask to see their identification badge, which will include a photo and a U.S. Department of Commerce watermark.

All census takers will wear masks and follow local public health guidelines during door-to-door canvassing and takers may also carry Census Bureau bags and other equipment with the Census Bureau logo. If no one is home when the census taker visits, he/she will leave a notice of their visit with information about how to respond online, by phone or by mail.

Citizens who respond online at 2020Census.gov or by phone to 844-330-2020, are less likely to have a census taker visit their home to collect a response. #CherokeeCounts #2020Census #CherokeeGA #CherokeeCounty

post_text:
Guess what day it is? It‚Äôs #InternationalCatDay! üê±Cats have been our companions for at least 9,500 years and are currently the most popular pet in the world. Cats are a beloved member of many households around the world. But a cat is so much more than a companion animal. Studies show that interactions with cats may improve health and reduce physical responses to stress. Having a cat in the household may also improve psychological health by providing emotional support to people suffering from depression, anxiety and loneliness.

If you want to celebrate International Cat Day by doing something special for a feline, then consider adopting a cat from the Cherokee County Animal Shelter. By doing so you can provide a lucky cat with a lifetime of love and safety and perhaps even improve your well-being while you‚Äôre at it! #CherokeeGA #CherokeeCounty

Today we are off to Mica/Conn's Creek for this week‚Äôs #TravelingTuesdays!
‚ÄúThe community of Mica was located about eight miles east of Ball Ground and sprung up as a result of the gold rush in the area. Kenneth Krakow in his ‚ÄúGeorgia Place-Names‚Äù says Mica was named for the gold and mica mines in the area. Stancil‚Äôs Store was established in 1912 in the area and continues to serve the community.‚Äù I've been having trouble finding the community boundary line between Conn's Creek and Mica, can anyone tell me what the boundary line is between them or if there is a line at all? It would be greatly appreciated! It's common enough for smaller communities to overlap some and even more common for larger communities to expand over and eventually encompass smaller communities while they grow.
Cherokee County, Georgia: A History
Written by Rebecca Johnston
#CherokeeCountyHistoricalSociety #CCHS #localhistory #Mica

Get ready for a tasty treat because today is #NationalIceCreamDay! In 1984, President Ronald Reagan designated the third Sunday of the month as National Ice Cream Day.

Americans consume, on average, about 23 gallons of ice cream each year. Ice cream has historically been a key feature of American communities. According to an IDFA survey, most ice cream companies are family owned and have been in operation for more than 50 years! Here‚Äôs more sweet news: Ice cream companies help support the U.S. economy, contributing more than $11 billion directly to the national economy and supporting more than 26,000 direct jobs that generate $1.6 billion in direct wages, according to IDFA‚Äôs Dairy Delivers¬Æ. In 2017, about 1.4 billion gallons of ice cream and related frozen desserts were produced in the United States. What flavor will you celebrate with? #CherokeeGA #CherokeeCounty

The Cherokee County Animal Shelter wants to help the Cherokee County pets of those who have been furloughed or lost wages due to the Covid-19 Pandemic. The shelter secured a grant and created a Virtual Rabies Clinic for qualifying pets. The clinic will continue to Aug. 28 (or until grant funding is exhausted). üê∂üê±

How do you participate?
-Be a Cherokee County resident who has been furloughed due to Covid-19 Pandemic.
-Register at the following link: https://forms.gle/PNMGvsZv2LSiGKKDA
Vouchers will be mailed to eligible participants and must be used within a month of issue at a participating vets office.
*Rabies vaccination is an annual vaccine required by Cherokee County Ordinance (Sec. 10-41).

Mark your calendar! The 2020 General Primary Election Runoff - Election Day is August 11. The last day to register to vote in this Runoff is July 13. If, in the June 9 General Primary, a voter voted a Republican or Nonpartisan ballot OR did not vote in the General Primary AND are in House District 20, 21 or County Commission 2 they are eligible to vote in the August 11 Runoff.

Advanced Voting is set to begin July 20. Voters can find their polling locations and registration status at www.mvp.sos.ga.gov.

post_text:
The Cherokee County Animal Shelter wants to help Cherokee County pets of those who have been furloughed or lost wages due to the Covid-19 Pandemic. We have secured a grant and created a Virtual Rabies Clinic for those pets that will be continued through August 28th (Or until grant funding is exhausted).
How do you participate?
-Be a Cherokee County resident who has been furloughed due to Covid-19 Pandemic.
-Register at the following link: https://forms.gle/PNMGvsZv2LSiGKKDA
Vouchers will be mailed to eligible participants and must be used within a month of issue at a participating vets office.
*Rabies vaccination is an annual vaccine required by Cherokee County Ordinance (Sec. 10-41).

Huge congratulations to our Fleet Management Department! They were recently awarded the Blue Seal of Excellence from the National Institute of Automotive Service Excellence (ASE) for the second straight year.

One of only six counties in the state of Georgia to achieve the designation, the department had to meet certain criteria as identified by the ASE, including requiring advanced certification of technicians. #CherokeeCounty #CherokeeGa

post_text:
Cherokee County's participation rate for the 2020 Census has been hovering around 62 percent. We are encouraging another strong push for our community to complete its Census. If your household has already completed it, please encourage your friends, coworkers, neighbors and family to do the same. Our communities will benefit greatly from the resources based on Census data which funds schools, hospitals, roads, public works and other vital programs.

Please complete your 2020 Census and ask at least three or four others to join you in responding to the Census. All of the information provided is confidential and secure and will only be used to provide Census data and resources.
For more information, or to complete your census, visit 2020census.gov. #2020Census #CherokeeCounts

post_text: We have BIG NEWS! In partnership with the Georgia Department of Transportation, we are set to begin making several intersection improvements along Ga. 140 to help ease traffic congestion. The first improvement project will add right-turn lanes on all approaches, correct sight distance issues and add sidewalks on all approaches at Ga. 140 at East Cherokee Drive. The project will be under construction for a year and is set to begin this summer. To read more about the Ga. 140 projects and other upcoming traffic projects, visit www.cherokeega.com/Roadway-Splost-Program. #CherokeeCounty #CherokeeGA #SPLOSTinAction #YourTaxDollarsAtWork

post_text:
As the Fourth of July approaches, Cherokee County Fire and Emergency Services urges citizens to use caution when enjoying fireworks. In 2018, fireworks started 19,500 fires that resulted in 46 civilian injuries and 5 deaths.

Cherokee County Fire Chief, Tim Prather offers the following safety suggestions for this Fourth of July:

‚Ä¢ Purchase fireworks from a licensed fireworks dealer.
‚Ä¢ Observe all state laws regarding the use of fireworks.
‚Ä¢ Read labels before igniting any fireworks.
‚Ä¢ Never allow children to ignite fireworks.
‚Ä¢ Wear safety glasses when shooting fireworks.
‚Ä¢ Light only one firework at a time.
‚Ä¢ Use fireworks outdoors in an area away from buildings and vehicles.
‚Ä¢ Have a garden hose or bucket of water nearby.

In accordance with state law, fireworks are to end no later than 11:59 p.m. on July 3 & 4.

#CherokeeCounty #CherokeeGa #CherokeeCountyFire

post_text: Today, we celebrate the adoption of the American flag, otherwise known as Flag Day. But do you know the history behind this day? ü§∑ When the American Revolution broke out in 1775, the colonists weren‚Äôt fighting united under a single flag. Instead, most regiments participating in the war for independence against the British fought under their own flags. In June of 1775, the Second Continental Congress met in Philadelphia to create the Continental Army‚Äîa unified colonial fighting force‚Äîwith the hopes of more organized battle against its colonial oppressors. This led to the creation of what was, essentially, the first ‚ÄúAmerican‚Äù flag, the Continental Colors. To learn more about this day click here: http://ow.ly/GthM50A6f9U #CherokeeGa #CherokeeCty #FlagDay

The City of Woodstock and unincorporated Cherokee County residents in the area of Arnold Mill Road will see fresh paving in the coming days!

As part of the 2020 Resurfacing Project, C.W. Matthews Contracting Company will begin paving Monday, June 8 in parts of the City of Woodstock.

The resurfacing project is subject to change depending on weather and other unknown factors. Resurfacing work is expected to take place Monday through Friday from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m., until the project is complete.

On Arnold Mill Road, C.W. Matthews will pave 3.54 miles, Barnes Road to the Woodstock City Limits, as well as 1.01 miles on Barnes Road from Trickum Road to Arnold Mill Road.

Just outside the City of Woodstock, C.W. Matthews will pave 2.57 miles of Lower Birmingham Road, from Batesville Road to the Fulton County Line. #CherokeeGa #CherokeeCtyGa #WoodstockGa

post_text:
In honor of #WorldEnvironmentDay we would like to spotlight The Etowah River.

The Upper Coosa River Basin (home to the Etowah River) ranges from Southeastern Tennessee and North Central Georgia to Weiss Dam in Northeast Alabama and holds an incredible array of aquatic species.

No other river basin in North America has a higher percentage of endemic species than the Upper Coosa River Basin. Thirty (30) different species of fishes, mussels, snails and crayfishes call the waters of the Coosa‚Äîand no where else‚Äîhome. Researchers call the Upper Coosa Basin a ‚Äúglobally significant biological treasure.‚Äù

To learn more about the Etowah River and Etowah Darter click here: https://coosa.org/our-rivers/

Got questions about the murder hornet? üôã‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è The folks at UGA Extension- Cherokee County Georgia are here to help!

At this time there have been no confirmed cases of this hornet‚Äôs presence in Georgia or anywhere outside of Washington state. Other wasps and hornets already residents in our state that may be confused with the Asian giant hornet are:
‚Ä¢ Cicada killers, Sphecius speciosus, size range 0.6 ‚Äì 2 inches long (15 ‚Äì 50mm)
‚Ä¢ European hornets, Vespa crabro, size range 1-1.4 inches (25-35mm)
‚Ä¢ Southern yellowjackets, Vespula squamosa, size range 0.5inches (12mm)
‚Ä¢ Baldfaced hornets, Dolichovespula maculata, size range 0.75 inches (19mm)

The Asian giant hornet and cicada killer may be similar in size but very different in coloration. The Center for Invasive Species and Ecosystem Health have put together an ‚ÄúAsian Giant Hornet and its SE US Lookalikes‚Äù photographic fact sheet (link below) which is extremely helpful for distinguishing between the different species in our state.

How do we stay connected to those around us while still following social distancing guidelines? GPB connects millions of Georgians every day through television, radio, digital initiatives and innovative educational programming. In this time of social distancing, we‚Äôve launched the #myGAneighborhood campaign as a way to encourage neighborhood support and spread joy in our communities.

Whether you‚Äôre sending positive thoughts with chalk art messages on your sidewalks and streets, leading a neighborhood activity or carrying out a good deed for neighbors in need, we want to hear from you.

GPB will be tracking submissions and sharing some of our favorites on social media and in special television segments.

For complete details on how to participate, visit gpb.org/neighborhood

post_text: The new Cherokee County Fire Station #9, located on Reinhardt College Parkway in north Canton, is in the final stages of being completed. üöí
shared_text:
Cherokee County Fire and Emergency Services
May 12 at 3:29 PM ¬∑

The new Cherokee County Fire Station #9, located on Reinhardt College Parkway in north Canton, is in the final stages of being completed.

According to Division Chief, Dean Floyd, ‚ÄúThe contractor is on schedule to be complete the first week in June, pending any unforeseen changes like weather or COVID 19. Once the building has been turned over to the fire department, we are hoping to have firefights working out of the new station by the end of July or the first of August.‚Äù

The new facility will replace the old North Canton Volunteer Fire Department which was built by local volunteers around 1973, but was never intended to house full-time firefighters. The new station, which will be located across the road from the old Fire Station #9, will also provide safer living conditions and will allow firefighters to have a quicker response to emergency incidents.

The Cherokee County Elections & Voter Registration office has received lots of inquires on the absentee ballot envelops that have been mailed out.

Please note: There is no white envelope with the absentee ballot! Please see the post below.
shared_text:
Cherokee County Elections & Voter Registration
April 28 at 10:00 AM ¬∑

Please do not tape or staple your ballot into the "Privacy Sleeve".

The Secretary of State‚Äôs office contracted with a vendor in Arizona to mail out the absentee ballots for the June 9, 2020 general primary. Instead of creating a white inner envelope and an outer envelope printed with an Oath, the vendor created a white paper ‚Äúsleeve‚Äù as the inner envelope. Apparently, the artwork being sent back and forth for approval looked the same as an envelope, until the miscommunication was recently discovered. The instructions say to enclose and securely seal the voted ballot in the smaller of the two envelopes, but don‚Äôt worry, the white folded paper sleeve will work just fine. Please put your voted ballot into the white paper sleeve and then place it into the Oath envelope, sign the Oath and return the ballot. Do not tape or staple the paper sleeve, because the ballot might become damaged as we remove it.

Instead of creating a white inner envelope and an outer envelope printed with an Oath, the vendor created a white paper ‚Äúsleeve‚Äù as the inner envelope. Apparently, the artwork being sent back and forth for approval looked the same as an envelope, until the miscommunication was recently discovered. The instructions say to enclose and securely seal the voted ballot in the smaller of the two envelopes, but don‚Äôt worry, the white folded paper sleeve will work just fine. Please put your voted ballot into the white paper sleeve and then place it into the Oath envelope, sign the Oath and return the ballot. Do not tape or staple the paper sleeve, because the ballot might become damaged as we remove it.

Widespread severe weather is still expected tonight (and into early Monday morning) across much of north and central Georgia.

Overview: Severe storms will develop this evening and overspread much of north & central Georgia through the night.

SPC's Moderate Risk (level 4 of 5) has been expanded east to include the western portion of Georgia (including the Atlanta metro area). The Enhanced Risk (level 3 of 5) covers the remainder of north & central GA.

Storm Threats:

* Tornadoes, a few strong (EF2+) long-track possible
* Damaging winds w/ localized gusts > 75 MPH possible
* Large hail (quarter to golf-ball sized)
* Very heavy rain (training of storms could lead to localized flash flooding)

Stay safe and please continue to monitor the weather!

The Georgia Department of Public Health has created a Specimen Point of Collection (SPOC) in Cherokee County. The SPOC site will be open starting today. At this time testing is NOT open to the general public and will be limited to persons 60 and older with symptoms of CoVid-19.

Persons 60 and older with symptoms of CoVid-19 must contact their Healthcare Provider to be screened and entered into the Public Health Referral System. They will receive an appointment time and ‚ÄúPerson Under Investigation‚Äù (PUI) number. Those without a PUI number will not be tested at this time.

Again, testing is NOT open to the general public and only those aged 60 and older with a referral from their healthcare provider and assigned PUI number will be tested.

The drive up testing site is located at the Cherokee County Government Complex at 7545 Main St, Woodstock GA 30188 #CherokeeCOVID19

Hours of Operation:
Monday - Thursday 9am to 3pm
Friday 9am to 12pm

If there is substantial spread in your area, all gatherings should be cancelled.

March 14 at 8:55 PM ¬∑

Due to mounting concerns over the Covid-19 Virus and the current State of Emergency, Secretary Raffensperger has moved the Presidential Preference Primary (and attached special elections) from March 24, 2020 to coincide with the State Primary scheduled for May 19, 2020.

The Presidential Preference Primary (and associated special elections) has been moved/postponed. It has not been cancelled.

Every vote already cast, whether by mail or in person, WILL be counted in May for the Presidential Preference Primary and any local special elections along with votes cast in the state primary.

All residential building permit applications and new business license applications can be emailed directly to the DSC representatives at dsc@cherokeega.com. All payments can be paid through the web portal or by contacting the DSC at 770-721-7810. https://cityview.cherokeega.com/cvprodportal.

All other permit and development applications are available on the DSC webpage. https://www.cherokeega.com/DSC.

Any questions can be directed to the DSC at 770-721-7810 or email dsc@cherokeega.com. #CherokeeCOVID19

Cherokee County government officials are closely monitoring novel coronavirus with local and state emergency management and public health officials, and are prepared in case the virus spreads to our area. While two cases have been reported in Fulton County (they are isolated in their home per Gov. Brian Kemp's office), no cases have been reported in Cherokee County. We are sharing the following information with citizens of Cherokee County as a precaution. We encourage you to practice good handwashing for at least 20 seconds with soap and water multiple times a day (an alcohol-based hand sanitizer is a good back up when soap and water are not available). These practices will also protect you against the flu, which has had high activity for 15 weeks, according to the CDC. Key indicators that track flu activity remain high but have decreased for the second week in a row.

Learn more about novel coronavirus, CONVID-19, by reviewing this video.

shared_text:
Cherokee County, GA Emergency Management
February 28 at 5:41 PM ¬∑

[! 4:30 PM Friday - Feb 28 Update !] Winter Weather Potential tonight into early Saturday

Tonight/Saturday:

North Georgia will be impacted by a second quickly-moving system late tonight into early Saturday morning, bringing another chance for light snow to portions of north Georgia.

The greatest snow chances are expected in far northeastern Georgia, with accumulations of 1/2 to 1 inch possible in the higher elevations above 2000 ft
No accumulations expected elsewhere across north Georgia.
Any light snow should diminish by 5-7 AM.
A Special Weather Statement has been issued accordingly.
Morning lows in far north Georgia will drop to the upper 20s to low 30s, with mid 30s elsewhere across north Georgia. Temperatures will rise into the upper 30s and 40s across far north Georgia on Saturday afternoon, with upper 40s to low 50s elsewhere across north Georgia. Afternoon winds will increase to 15-20 mph out of the northwest with gusts of 25-35 mph. A Wind Advisory cannot be ruled out with future updates.

NOTICE: Hickory Flat Area Plan Public Input Meetings - Postponement

The Cherokee County Board of Commissioners have decided to postpone the public input meetings for the Hickory Flat Plan for the following reasons:

1) The County wants to receive the completed Market Study from Bleakly Advisory Group.

2) The County is waiting to hear from GDOT and the ARC on funding status for a number of the transportation projects along SR 140 that will affect the area.

3) More coordination is needed with the City of Holly Springs and their plans for the area.

The public meetings scheduled for February 11th and March 11th, along with the stakeholder meetings on February 26th and March 25th are hereby postponed until further notice.

In the meantime, Planning Staff will be working on gathering additional information and resources to aid the community in developing their plan. A new press release will be issued in the future once the meetings are rescheduled.

Please contact Cherokee County Planning Staff at pluse@cherokeega.com or (678) 493-6101 with any questions or comments.

We have a weather update!

Overview:

Strong thunderstorms are expected today just ahead of a strengthening cold front. The line of thunderstorms will continue eastward overnight and into Thursday with strong/severe storms possible for much of the day.

Primary Hazards & Impacts:
‚Ä¢ Damaging wind gusts in excess of 60 MPH
‚Ä¢ A few brief tornadoes embedded within the line
‚Ä¢ Heavy rainfall
o North of I-85: 2" to 4" with locally higher amounts up to 6"
o South of I-85: 1.5" to 3"
‚Ä¢ Heavy Rain Impacts:
o Very quick rises on smaller, fast responding creeks/streams, especially in urban areas and higher terrain
o Minor flooding on mainstream rivers is possible, mainly across north Georgia
o Localized Flash Flooding
Timing:
‚Ä¢ Wednesday Night: Mainly for portions of west Georgia, including the Atlanta Metro and Macon areas
‚Ä¢ Thursday: Thunderstorms can be expected much of the day as the system continues to move east across the state

post_text:
A strong cold front will bring chances for some strong to severe storms to portions of north and central Georgia later tonight and into Tuesday. Current timing for showers/storms entering north west Georgia looks to be just slightly later than previously thought. Below are our updated thoughts on main threats and timing. We are in the Marginal Risk (level 1 out of 5) for severe weather. üå™

Main points:
‚Ä¢ Some storms could organize into a line or some broken line segments capable of strong to damaging wind gusts or even a brief tornado tonight and into Tuesday.
‚Ä¢ While the Storm Prediction Center (SPC) has included some western portions of the area in a Marginal Risk for severe weather with a Slight Risk up to the border (see graphic below), the threat could be expanded farther eastward.
‚Ä¢ Greatest chances entering NW Georgia after 8 PM this evening, then continuing overnight into early Tuesday farther south and east.
‚Ä¢ Heaviest rainfall is expected across north Georgia, where 1-2 inches are possible and isolated flooding cannot be ruled out.

DETOUR NOTICE

The Cherokee County Roadway Capital Program announces that Puckett Creek Road at SR 140 intersection will be closed to through traffic, from November 18, 2019 through December 3, 2019, for reconstruction of Puckett Creek Road associated with the SR 140 at Lower Burris Road / Puckett Creek Road Intersection Improvement project.

A posted detour will be provided during the duration of the construction. The detour route utilizes Sam Nelson Road. (see attached map)

Cherokee County appreciates the public‚Äôs patience during the detour period and requests that motorists obey the detour for their safety as well as for the safety of all contractors‚Äô personnel.

Questions regarding the detour should be directed to the Cherokee County Roadway Capital Program at (678)493-6077.

Please share!

Starting Monday am 10/7/2019, Cherokee County Public Works will begin the first section of Little Road Project. This will include clearing and reconstruction of Little Road between Hickory Road and East Cherokee Drive. **This will be for an indefinite length of time.** Public Works and other utility companies will be working on this project during daylight hours until the project is complete. The road will be open to local and thru traffic but expect long delays. Please use alternate routes if possible.

For questions please contact Public Works 770 345 5842.
